05531nam a22008055i 9780812205213DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979740937  a97808122052137 a10.9783/97808122052132doi  a(DE-B1597)449488  a(OCoLC)793012721  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0070002bisacsh1 aLupton, Christina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKnowing Books :bThe Consciousness of Mediation in Eighteenth-Century Britain /cChristina Lupton. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction. Giving Power to the Medium -- tChapter 1. Powerlessness as Entertainment -- tChapter 2. What It-Narratives Know About Their Authors -- tChapter 3. The Theory of Paper -- tChapter 4. Sermons Written on the Screen of Print -- tChapter 5. Gray and Mackenzie Printing on the Wall -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe eighteenth century has long been associated with realism and objective description, modes of representation that deemphasize writing. But in the middle decades of the century, Christina Lupton observes, authors described with surprising candor the material and economic facets of their own texts' production. In Knowing Books Lupton examines a variety of eighteenth-century sources, including sermons, graffiti, philosophical texts, and magazines, which illustrate the range and character of mid-century experiments with words announcing their status as physical objects. Books that "know" their own presence on the page and in the reader's hand become, in Lupton's account, tantalizing objects whose entertainment value competes with that of realist narrative.Knowing Books introduces these mid-eighteenth-century works as part of a long history of self-conscious texts being greeted as fashionable objects. Poststructuralist and Marxist approaches to literature celebrate the consciousness of writing and economic production as belonging to revolutionary understandings of the world, but authors of the period under Lupton's gaze expose the facts of mediation without being revolutionary. On the contrary, their explication of economic and material processes shores up their claim to material autonomy and economic success. Lupton uses media theory and close reading to suggest the desire of eighteenth-century readers to attribute sentience to technologies and objects that entertain them.Rather than a historical study of print technology, Knowing Books offers a humanist interpretation of the will to cede agency to media. This horizon of theoretical engagement makes Knowing Books at once an account of the least studied decades of the eighteenth century and a work of relevance for those interested in new attitudes toward media in the twenty-first.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aEnglish literaturex18th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLiterature publishingzGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aLiterature publishingzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aMediation in literature. 0aSelf-consciousness (Awareness) in literature. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Li